Perceptron

In a artificial neural network (ANN) consisting of only one layer, commonly referred to as a perceptron, we have the following components that constitute a function f(x)=yf(x) = yf(x)=y, where f:Rn×1→Rf: \mathbb{R}^{n \times 1} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}f:Rn×1→R:

Inputs

The inputs will be denoted by the variable xtx^txt, where xt=[x1x2…xn]x^t = \begin{bmatrix}x_1 & x_2 & \dots & x_n\end{bmatrix}xt=[x1​​x2​​…​xn​​], with each xi∈Rx_i \in \mathbb{R}xi​∈R and for xxx as a vector, we have x∈Rn×1x \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times 1}x∈Rn×1. The notation xtx^txt is based on the transposition of the vector xxx. The variable x0x_0x0​ will be reserved to represent the bias in the future; therefore, the real nnn-inputs of the perceptron will always be referred to through i=1,…,ni = 1, \dots, ni=1,…,n.

Weights

The weights will be responsible for modulating the nnn-inputs xxx. Thus, concerning the first layer, where the inputs will always be the vector xxx, we will always have wt=[w1w2…wn]w^t = \begin{bmatrix} w_1 & w_2 & \dots & w_n \end{bmatrix}wt=[w1​​w2​​…​wn​​], where each wi∈Rw_i \in \mathbb{R}wi​∈R, and for the vector www, we have w∈Rn×1w \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times 1}w∈Rn×1 with the quantity of nnn-inputs of xxx equal to the nnn-weights of www. The weight w0w_0w0​ will be reserved to represent the bias also.

Transfer Function z(x)z(x)z(x)

Thus, z(x)z(x)z(x) is responsible for relating the nnn-inputs with their respective nnn-weights to generate zzz, serving as the transfer function. As we are currently defining a layer, this being the first one, z:Rn×1→Rz: \mathbb{R}^{n \times 1} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}z:Rn×1→R. To define the function z(x)z(x)z(x), we can do so in two ways:

z=[w1w2…wn]⋅[x1x2⋮xn]+b=∑i=1nxiwi+b=wt⋅x+bz = \begin{bmatrix} w_1 & w_2 & \dots & w_n \end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix} x_1\\ x_2 \\ \vdots \\ x_n \end{bmatrix} + b = \sum_{i=1}^{n}x_iw_i + b = w^t \cdot x+b z=[w1​​w2​​…​wn​​]⋅​x1​x2​⋮xn​​​+b=i=1∑n​xi​wi​+b=wt⋅x+b

In the above definition, we have the affine function. However, we can also define the bias as b=w0b = w_0b=w0​ and x0=1x_0 = 1x0​=1 by substituting the bias bbb in the affine function with a neuron whose weight serves as the bias, and its input is always set to 1. In this method, where the bias acts as a weight, we have a linear function.

z=[w0=bw1w2…wn]⋅[x0=1x1x2⋮xn]=∑i=0nxiwi=wt⋅xz = \begin{bmatrix} w_0 = b & w_1 & w_2 & \dots & w_n \end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix} x_0 = 1\\ x_1 \\ x_2 \\ \vdots \\ x_n \end{bmatrix} = \sum_{i=0}^{n}x_iw_i = w^t \cdot x z=[w0​=b​w1​​w2​​…​wn​​]⋅​x0​=1x1​x2​⋮xn​​​=i=0∑n​xi​wi​=wt⋅x

In the graphical representation below, we illustrate the processing of the nnn-inputs xix_ixi​ through the respective weights wiw_iwi​, resulting in zzz. This is denoted as the transfer function.

Activation Function φ(z)\varphi(z)φ(z)

The activation function is responsible for introducing nonlinearity into the system. Therefore, it always receives the value of zzz. The activation function can be defined in various forms such as sigmoid, hyperbolic tangent, rectified linear unit, etc. In this topic, we will not focus on the behavior of each function yet but rather on how the system is structured with it. Thus, for only one layer of neurons with a single neuron, we have φ:R→R\varphi: \mathbb{R} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}φ:R→R:

φ(z)=φ(wt⋅x)=φ(∑i=0nxiwi)=y\varphi(z) = \varphi(w^t \cdot x) = \varphi(\sum_{i=0}^{n}x_iw_i) = y φ(z)=φ(wt⋅x)=φ(i=0∑n​xi​wi​)=y

Below is the representation of a single operating artificial neuron.

So, from the perspective of a perceptron, we can define the function f(x)=yf(x) = yf(x)=y, where f:Rn×1→Rf: \mathbb{R}^{n \times 1} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}f:Rn×1→R:

f(x)=φ(wt⋅x)=yf(x) = \varphi(w^t \cdot x) = y f(x)=φ(wt⋅x)=y

Note that in the above definitions, we used the linear function mode. Also, in the next topic, we will not use the notation wtw^twt indicating the transpose of the matrix. Therefore, it will be implicit that in the multiplication between layer inputs and their weights, the weight matrix will be transposed. In this case, we will see it as follows: z(x)=w⋅xz(x) = w \cdot xz(x)=w⋅x.

Layer with Multiple Neurons

In the previous definition, we had a layer with only one neuron. In this topic, we will define the behavior of a layer with iii-neurons. Thus, the function f(x)=yf(x) = yf(x)=y will not define only the behavior of one neuron but of iii-neurons.

Therefore, we will have the definition of fL(x)f^L(x)fL(x) where LLL is the index of the layer. Each layer LLL can have iii neurons. So, for each neuron iii, we will have an output of the transfer function zi1z_{i}^1zi1​ in the layer f1(x)f^1(x)f1(x).

As an example, let's analyze zi1=wi1⋅xz_{i}^1 = w_{i}^1 \cdot xzi1​=wi1​⋅x. For wi1w_{i}^1wi1​, which represents the weights of neuron iii in layer 1, we have:

wi1=[w0iw1i…wni],∀wni∃xnw_{i}^1 = \begin{bmatrix} w_{0_i} & w_{1_i} & \dots & w_{n_i}\end{bmatrix}, \forall w_{n_i}\exists x_n wi1​=[w0i​​​w1i​​​…​wni​​​],∀wni​​∃xn​

Therefore, for input into the layer, there will always be a weight www. However, this does not imply that there should be iii neurons for each nnn-inputs. So, for the function z(x)z(x)z(x), where z1:Rn×1→Ri×1z^1: \mathbb{R}^{n \times 1} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^{i \times 1}z1:Rn×1→Ri×1, we have:

z1(x)=[w01=b1w11w21…wn1w02=b2w12w22…wn2⋮⋮⋮⋱⋮w0i=biw1iw2i…wni]⋅[x0x1x2⋮xn]=[z1z2⋮zi]z^1(x) = \begin{bmatrix}w_{0_1}=b_1 & w_{1_1} & w_{2_1} & \dots & w_{n_1} \\w_{0_2}=b_2 & w_{1_2} & w_{2_2} & \dots & w_{n_2} \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ w_{0_i}=b_i & w_{1_i} & w_{2_i} & \dots & w_{n_i} \end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix} x_0 \\ x_1 \\ x_2 \\ \vdots \\ x_n \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} z_1 \\ z_2 \\ \vdots \\ z_i \end{bmatrix} z1(x)=​w01​​=b1​w02​​=b2​⋮w0i​​=bi​​w11​​w12​​⋮w1i​​​w21​​w22​​⋮w2i​​​……⋱…​wn1​​wn2​​⋮wni​​​​⋅​x0​x1​x2​⋮xn​​​=​z1​z2​⋮zi​​​

We can also represent the transfer function in the following manner. Note that after defining the function below, we denote Z1Z^1Z1 in uppercase for the output vector of layer and WiW_{i}Wi​ for the weights of neuron iii, facilitating comprehension:

Z1=[z1=∑k=0nwk1xkz2=∑k=0nwk2xk⋮zi=∑k=0nwkixk]=W1⋅XZ^1 =\begin{bmatrix} z_1 = \sum_{k=0}^{n} w_{k_1}x_k \\ z_2 = \sum_{k=0}^{n} w_{k_2}x_k \\ \vdots \\ z_i = \sum_{k=0}^{n} w_{k_i}x_k \end{bmatrix} = W^1 \cdot X Z1=​z1​=∑k=0n​wk1​​xk​z2​=∑k=0n​wk2​​xk​⋮zi​=∑k=0n​wki​​xk​​​=W1⋅X

Applying now the activation function φ\varphiφ, which will generate f1(X)=Yf^1(X) = Yf1(X)=Y where f1:Rn×1→Ri×1f^1: \mathbb{R}^{n \times 1} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^{i \times 1}f1:Rn×1→Ri×1, we have:

Multilayer Perceptron (MLP)

Based on the general function from the previous topic, we know that Z1=W1⋅XZ^1 = W^1 \cdot XZ1=W1⋅X, where XXX refers to the nnn-inputs, W1W^1W1 represents the weights of each iii-neuron in the first layer, and Z1Z^1Z1 denotes the output vector of the transfer function of the first layer. With this understanding, we can apply LLL more layers to the system, where the input of layer LLL is the output vector of layer L−1L-1L−1:

ZL=WL⋅ZL−1L=1,…,LZ^L = W^L \cdot Z^{L-1} \quad L=1, \dots, L ZL=WL⋅ZL−1L=1,…,L

With this in mind, when L−1=0L-1 = 0L−1=0, we understand that we are referring to the input layer XXX. The representation below will be clearer:

Therefore, with this structure in place, it becomes clear that in the last layer LLL, we can apply the activation function φ(Z)\varphi(Z)φ(Z) to obtain the output vector YYY:

Y=φ(ZL)=φ(WL⋅ZL−1)Y = \varphi(Z^L) = \varphi(W^L \cdot Z^{L-1}) Y=φ(ZL)=φ(WL⋅ZL−1)

Definition 1: A Multilayer perceptron is a function F:Rn→RmF: \mathbb{R}^n \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^mF:Rn→Rm. It is an nnn-LLL-mmm perceptron (nnn-inputs, LLL hidden layers, and mmm outputs) if it is a function of the form

F(X)=φ(fL(fL−1(…f1(X)))),forXt=[x0x1…xn]F(X) = \varphi(f^L(f^{L-1}(\dots f^1(X)))), \quad \text{for} \quad X^t=\begin{bmatrix} x_0 & x_1 & \dots & x_n \end{bmatrix} F(X)=φ(fL(fL−1(…f1(X)))),forXt=[x0​​x1​​…​xn​​]

Where f1(X)=W1⋅Xf^1(X) = W^1 \cdot Xf1(X)=W1⋅X and for the remaining layers fi(Zi−1)=Wi⋅Zi−1f^i(Z^{i-1}) = W^i \cdot Z^{i-1}fi(Zi−1)=Wi⋅Zi−1.

Notice that the usability of the activation function may vary. For example, in some problems, we may use the activation function at the output of each layer, while in others, we may not. For regression tasks in ANN, we won't use the activation layer in fL(ZL−1)f^L(Z^{L-1})fL(ZL−1), where as for classification problems, we may utilize the activation function in layer LLL.

Based on this, we have the freedom to create structures depending on the problem at hand. We will explore the application of this further ahead.

Theoretical Learning Algorithm

Let's consider a cost function E(W)E(W)E(W), where it represents the error value between the output of the layer and the expected value. The objective of this function is to provide a method that, by modifying the values of WWW, we can reduce the error indicated by the function E(W)E(W)E(W) until it is the smallest possible value.

For this, we can apply the gradient of the function E(W)E(W)E(W). Let's recall the gradient theorem below:

Theorem 1 (Gradient of a function). Let E:Rn→RE: R^n \rightarrow RE:Rn→R be a differenciable function in the neighbourhood of some points W=[w0w1…wi]W = \begin{bmatrix} w_0 & w_1 & \dots & w_i\end{bmatrix}W=[w0​​w1​​…​wi​​] where iii represents the number of neurons in this hypothetical layer. Then, the gradient of EEE at WWW, denote by ∇E(W)\nabla E(W)∇E(W),

  1. represents the slope of the tangent line to the function EEE at the point www;
  2. points in the direction in which the function EEE most rapidly increases; thus, −∇E-\nabla E−∇E indicates the direction of fastest decreasing;
  3. is orthogonal to the level surfaces (generalization of the concept of a level curve for a function of two variables) of EEE, i.e., those of the form E(W)=kE(W) = kE(W)=k for a constant kkk

Example of ∇f\nabla f∇f:

To facilitate understanding, let's define the function f:R2→Rf: \mathbb{R}^2 \rightarrow \mathbb{R}f:R2→R such that:

f(x,y)=x2+y2f(x, y) = x^2 + y^2 f(x,y)=x2+y2

If we visualize the function graphically, we have:

Based on the function f(x,y)f(x, y)f(x,y), we can define −∇f(x,y)-\nabla f(x, y)−∇f(x,y) according to Theorem 1, item 2. Thus, we obtain a vector field with the following deduction:

−∇f(x,y)=[−∂f(x,y)∂x=−2x−∂f(x,y)∂y=−2y]- \nabla f(x, y) = \begin{bmatrix} -\dfrac{\partial f(x, y)}{\partial x} = -2x \\\\ -\dfrac{\partial f(x, y)}{\partial y} = -2y \end{bmatrix} −∇f(x,y)=​−∂x∂f(x,y)​=−2x−∂y∂f(x,y)​=−2y​​

To facilitate visualization, we can have a two-dimensional perspective (x,y)(x, y)(x,y) of the function f(x,y)f(x, y)f(x,y) where the coloration of the graph below will indicate the value of the zzz-axis. The intention is that the vectors point towards the minimum of the function, where the farther from the minimum, the greater the resultant of the vector, and the closer to the minimum, the smaller the resultant of the vector.

Having the gradient descent −∇f(x,y)-\nabla f(x, y)−∇f(x,y) at hand, we can define the algorithm responsible for updating the coordinates x,yx, yx,y until they converge to the minimum of the function f(x,y)f(x, y)f(x,y). Therefore, we can correct the values of xxx and yyy for iii iterations by adjusting the values based on the gradient descent.

In an empirical way, we can deduce that updating the values of xi+1x_{i+1}xi+1​ and yi+1y_{i+1}yi+1​ based on the gradient of xix_ixi​ and yiy_iyi​ is given by:

[xi+1yi+1]=[xiyi]−α[2xi2yi]\begin{bmatrix} x_{i+1} \\ y_{i+1}\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} x_{i} \\ y_{i}\end{bmatrix} - \alpha \begin{bmatrix} 2x_{i} \\ 2y_{i}\end{bmatrix} [xi+1​yi+1​​]=[xi​yi​​]−α[2xi​2yi​​]

The term α\alphaα will be introduced later in the proof of the gradient descent; for now, let's use it as a multiplier of the gradient, where the higher the α\alphaα, the greater the correction towards the minimum of the function, and the lower the α\alphaα, the smaller the correction towards the minimum of the function. This way, we can understand that:

f(xi+1,yi+1)≤f(xi,yi)f(x_{i+1}, y_{i+1}) \leq f(x_{i}, y_{i}) f(xi+1​,yi+1​)≤f(xi​,yi​)

Iterating iii times, we know that the condition f(x,y)=0f(x, y) = 0f(x,y)=0 will be true.

Below, we will see a simulation where we have coordinates x,yx, yx,y far from the minimum of the function. We know that, based on the vector field, we will have a straight-line trajectory towards the minimum of the function. Because of this, we implement a random variable τ∈[−0.1,0.1]\tau \in [-0.1, 0.1]τ∈[−0.1,0.1] to visualize how the gradient will perform. Therefore, the update relation of the coordinates will be:

[xi+1yi+1]=[xiyi]−α[2xi2yi]+[ττ]\begin{bmatrix} x_{i+1} \\ y_{i+1}\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} x_{i} \\ y_{i}\end{bmatrix} - \alpha \begin{bmatrix} 2x_{i} \\ 2y_{i}\end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} \tau \\ \tau \end{bmatrix} [xi+1​yi+1​​]=[xi​yi​​]−α[2xi​2yi​​]+[ττ​]
